The paper is about unsupervised neural machine translation, which falls under the category of natural language processing (NLP). Therefore, cs.CL (Computation and Language) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also proposes a new approach for training unsupervised translation systems, which involves editing real sentences from the target monolingual corpora. This approach involves neural networks and optimization, which are common topics in machine learning (ML) and artificial intelligence (AI), making cs.LG and cs.AI likely sub-categories as well. The paper also mentions the use of comparative translation loss, which is a type of loss function used in neural networks, making cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper uses experiments and evaluations to compare the proposed approach with previous state-of-the-art methods, which involves data analysis and statistics, making cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition) a possible sub-category as well.
